Advice for the layman: The Virtual Machine Guide
Welcome! If you are using a Mac, or if you are on Windows but prefer to use a full "Virtual Machine" instead of WSL, this guide is for you.

A Virtual Machine (VM) is a fake, software-based computer running inside your real computer. It acts like a completely separate machine. By using a "pre-built" image, we can skip the complicated Linux installation entirely and get you running in minutes.

Phase 1: Choose Your Sandbox (The Hypervisor)
To run a virtual machine, you need a program called a "hypervisor." Choose the one that fits your computer, download it, and install it like a normal app:

If you want to use VMware Player (Windows/Linux): See the VMware Instructions in Phase 3.

If you want to use Oracle VirtualBox (Windows/Older Intel Macs): See the VirtualBox Instructions in Phase 3.

If you want to use UTM (Newer M1/M2/M3 Macs): See the UTM Instructions in Phase 3.

If you are an advanced user who wants to build Linux from scratch: See the Advanced Appendix at the bottom of this page.

Phase 2: Download the Linux Brain (Pre-built Image)
Instead of building Linux from scratch, we are going to download a computer that is already set up and compressed into a single file.

Open your web browser and go to a trusted community image site like LinuxVMImages.com or OSBoxes.org.

Search for either CentOS 9 Stream or CentOS 10 Stream. Our backup software works perfectly on both!

Important: Download the file type that matches your hypervisor.

If using VirtualBox, download the VirtualBox Image (usually ends in .vdi or .ova).

If using VMware, download the VMware Image (usually ends in .vmdk or .ova).

If using UTM on a Mac, you can generally use the .ova or .qcow2 format.

Phase 3: Waking Up Your Machine
Now we will load that pre-built brain into your hypervisor.

For VMware:

Open VMware Workstation Player.

Click Open a Virtual Machine.

Find the .ova or .vmdk file you just downloaded and select it.

Give your new machine a name (like "Discord Archive") and click Import.

Once it finishes, click Play Virtual Machine.

For VirtualBox:

Open Oracle VirtualBox.

Go to File -> Import Appliance.

Select the .ova file you downloaded and click Next, then Finish.

Once it appears in your list on the left, click it and press the green Start arrow.

For UTM (Mac):

Open UTM.

Click the + button to create a new VM.

Click Virtualize, then select Linux.

Uncheck "Use Apple Virtualization" and click Browse to select your downloaded image file.

Follow the prompts to give it 4GB of Memory (RAM) and finish the setup. Press the play button to turn it on!

(Note: The website you downloaded the image from will provide the default username and password. It is usually something simple like centos for both the username and password!)

Phase 4: Bridging the Worlds (Getting files in and out)
Your Linux machine is locked in a secure box. To get our installer script inside, we need to map a shared folder between your real computer and the fake one.

If you are on Windows (VMware / VirtualBox):

In your hypervisor's top menu bar, look for Virtual Machine Settings.

Find the tab labeled Options or Shared Folders.

Turn it "On" and add your Windows Downloads folder.

Inside your Linux terminal, this folder will now magically appear at /mnt/hgfs/ (VMware) or /media/sf_Downloads/ (VirtualBox).

If you are on a Mac (UTM / VirtualBox):

UTM: While the VM is running, look at the top toolbar of the UTM window. Click the folder icon (Shared Directory) and select your Mac's Downloads folder. Inside Linux, you will find these files by navigating to the /media/ or /run/media/ directory.

Alternative Mac Method (Drag and Drop): If shared folders are fighting you, the easiest layman method is often built right in! In both VirtualBox and UTM, you can usually click on the dcordbk-installer.bash file on your Mac desktop, and simply drag and drop it right into the Linux virtual machine window.

Phase 5: Onward to Backup!
Your engine is built, fueled, and running.

You are now ready to install the Discord Archive Suite. Please return to the main "Advice for the layman" guide and begin at Phase 4: Installing the Backup Software. When that guide tells you to run the installer, just make sure you navigate to your new Shared Folder first!

Appendix: For Advanced Users (Installing from ISO)
If you do not want to use a pre-built community image and prefer to partition and install the OS manually, follow these steps:

Download the official DVD ISO for CentOS 9 Stream or CentOS 10 Stream from centos.org/download/.

Open your hypervisor and choose Create a New Virtual Machine (do not use "Import").

Point the virtual CD-ROM drive to your downloaded ISO file.

Allocate at least 2GB of RAM (4GB recommended) and a 20GB dynamically expanding virtual hard disk.

Boot the VM and follow the CentOS Anaconda installer. Ensure you set a root password, create a user with administrative privileges, and accept the default automatic storage partitioning.

Once rebooted, proceed to Phase 4 above to configure your shared folders.
